# Rust-Migration Conventions

This codebase is being prepared for a 1:1 migration to Rust. Rust has no classes,
only `struct` + `trait`. Write TypeScript so each unit maps mechanically.

## Behaviour = class implementing a trait, never a bare function

A vanilla function `f(input) -> output` becomes a `PureTransform` subclass.

```typescript
// âťŚ BAD â€” free function
export function gradientDescent(f, grad, x0, opts) { /* ... */ }

// âś… GOOD â€” config in constructor (struct fields), one input, one output
import {PureTransform} from '../shared/transform';
export class GradientDescent extends PureTransform<FirstOrderProblem, OptimResult> {
  constructor(private readonly opts: OptimOptions = {}) { super(); }
  transform(problem: FirstOrderProblem): OptimResult { /* ... */ }
}
```

- Configuration/parameters â†’ `readonly` constructor fields (Rust struct fields).
- Multiple arguments â†’ bundle into ONE named `Input` interface (Rust struct).
  No positional-argument-only functions.
- Base classes: `PureTransform` (pure/deterministic), `StatefulTransform`
  (`&mut self`), `FallibleTransform` (returns `Result`). See `shared/transform.ts`.
- Tiny enum-variant constructors (e.g. `num`, `add` for an AST) may stay as factories.

## Enums = discriminated unions, matched with `switch (x.kind)`

```typescript
export type Expr = NumNode | VarNode | BinNode;          // -> Rust enum
export interface NumNode { kind: 'num'; value: number; } // -> variant
switch (e.kind) { case 'num': /* ... */ }                // -> match
```

## Errors: `Result<T, E>` for expected failures, `throw` only for bugs

Use `shared/result.ts` (`ok`/`err`/`Result`) for recoverable outcomes (infeasible
solve, parse error, singular matrix). Reserve `throw` for invariant violations
(maps to Rust `panic!`).

## No ambient impurity â€” inject capabilities

Never call `Math.random()` / `Date.now()` directly. Inject a `RandomSource` /
`Clock` from `shared/capabilities.ts` so behaviour is deterministic and the Rust
side can pass the same dependency. Use `SeededRandom` in tests/sims.

## Numeric precision (two-tier â€” see docs/MIGRATION.md Â§5.4)

The engine cross-validates against five `float64` references (Python/numpy/
scipy/R/Octave), so the precision tier is chosen by the number's ROLE:

- **Numerical kernels** (linalg, optim, ODE, LP, eigen, stats, RL values) â†’
  `f64`. Do NOT use decimals here; it breaks cross-validation and is ~100Ă—
  slower. For long hot-loop accumulation use the Rust `precision::KahanAccumulator`.
- **`mathjs.BigNumber` usage** (the DES clock / time accrual, money & market
  balances, routing probabilities that sum to 1, the RV algebra) is EXACT
  COMPOUND BOOKKEEPING â†’ maps to Rust `rust_decimal::Decimal` (`des::shared::
  precision`), constructed via `bgn(x)` (= `math.bignumber(String(x))`) and read
  out via `to_f64` (= `Number(bn.toString())`). Keep using `bgn`/BigNumber in
  the TS for these; do not "simplify" them to `number`.
- **`Fraction`/exact `p/q`** â†’ Rust `num_rational::Rational64`.

## Types

- No `any` / `as any` in new code; prefer precise types and generics.
- Prefer `readonly` and immutable inputs; return new values.
- Shared math lives in `shared/linalg.ts` (`LinAlg`, `VecOps`), not file-local helpers.
